% ── Title ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\title{Causal Spectral-Truncation Kernels: Noncommutativity Certifies Drift
Detectability in Quantum Hardware}

\author{Molena Huynh}
\email{molena.huynh@jmp.com}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, North Carolina State University,
Raleigh, North Carolina 27695, USA}

\date{\today}

% ── Abstract ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\begin{abstract}
We introduce the causal spectral-truncation (CST) kernel, a
C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra-valued positive-definite kernel whose truncation
order $n$ controls the noncommutativity of the cross-channel products it represents,
and prove that this noncommutativity certifies detectability of hardware drift.
Fault-tolerant quantum computing is gated by drift whose most damaging mode ---
correlated decoherence from crosstalk, shared two-level-system baths, and flux noise
--- evades the per-channel monitors used in practice, because it leaves every
marginal and every instantaneous covariance unchanged while living entirely in the
\emph{ordered, lagged} cross-channel structure. CST resolves
this with a \emph{causal lower-shift} truncation, replacing the periodic Fourier
truncation of existing spectral-truncation kernels so it respects the arrow of time,
plus a reconstruction detector whose order admits a provable optimum. On a correlated-decoherence benchmark with matched marginals and matched stationary
covariance, every commutative monitor detects at chance
(ROC-AUC $\approx0.5$), whereas the noncommutative CST kernel reaches ROC-AUC~$0.90$
through a sharp optimal order $n{=}2$ that we certify analytically as the detection
analog of the representation--complexity trade-off. The same kernel also forecasts
coherence, $72\%$ over persistence eight steps ahead,
where noncommutativity is provably unnecessary --- an operational rule: match the
kernel's noncommutativity to the geometry of the drift. Training-free and
hardware-agnostic, the pipeline installs with \texttt{pip} and deterministically
regenerates every figure and table on a single CPU in seconds, delivering both a
certificate for noncommutative monitoring and a reproducible reliability toolbox.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

% ── Introduction ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Introduction}

Quantum processors are not static devices. The relaxation time \T, the dephasing
time \Ttwo, single- and two-qubit gate fidelities, readout-assignment error, and
tunable-coupling parameters all evolve continuously with temperature, flux noise,
two-level-system dynamics, and recalibration history
\citep{krantz2019guide,kjaergaard2020superconducting}. This drift is more than a
nuisance. In the noisy intermediate-scale quantum (NISQ) regime it limits the
depth of usable circuits \citep{preskill2018nisq}; in the fault-tolerant regime it
threatens the foundational assumption that physical error rates stay below
threshold long enough for error correction to suppress logical errors
\citep{google2023surfacecode,arute2019supremacy}. As processors scale to hundreds
and then thousands of qubits, deciding \emph{when} a device has drifted out of
specification, and \emph{which} qubits or intervals warrant the expensive
intervention of recalibration, becomes a data problem at a scale manual inspection
cannot meet. Reliability monitoring is, in this sense, a near-term bottleneck of
its own.

The hallmark of the most damaging drift is that it is not confined to a single
channel. Control crosstalk, shared two-level-system baths, and correlated flux
noise couple the errors of neighboring qubits and of distinct calibration
channels, frequently with a \emph{propagation delay}: a disturbance that perturbs
one qubit's coherence reappears, lagged, in a neighbor's readout or coupling phase
\citep{krantz2019guide}. Such \emph{correlated decoherence} is precisely the
failure mode that quantum error correction is least able to absorb, and precisely
the mode that per-channel, level-based monitors are worst equipped to see: an event
can leave every marginal distribution and every instantaneous correlation unchanged
while residing entirely in the \emph{ordered, lagged} cross-channel structure. A
monitor blind to that structure is blind to the drift, and no amount of per-channel
sensitivity recovers it. The established toolbox for diagnosing such errors ---
randomized benchmarking~\citep{magesan2011rb}, statistical drift
tracking~\citep{proctor2020drift}, and dedicated crosstalk-error
detection~\citep{sarovar2020crosstalk} --- relies on purpose-built characterization
circuits executed as separate experiments; we ask instead what can be inferred
\emph{passively}, from the multivariate calibration telemetry a processor already
logs, with no additional circuits and no labels.

This failure mode implicates a different model of monitoring altogether --- an
operator-algebraic one. A window of calibration telemetry is a multivariate
stochastic process and is naturally an element of a matrix algebra over the
channels; which cross-channel, cross-time interactions a monitor can resolve is
then exactly the question of which products in that algebra it computes --- the
setting of kernel methods and operator- and vector-valued kernel
learning~\citep{scholkopf2002kernels,micchelli2005vector}, whose unsupervised face
--- comparing distributions through kernel mean
embeddings~\citep{muandet2017kme} --- is precisely what an unlabeled drift detector
requires. Commutative kernels, whose feature products are insensitive to the order
or relative lag of their factors, cannot represent ordered lagged interactions at
all. The recent spectral-truncation kernels of
Hashimoto et~al.\ make this precise for functional data: truncating the algebra of
multiplication operators on the torus to finite Toeplitz matrices yields a family
of C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra-valued kernels whose noncommutativity,
governed by a single truncation parameter, captures interactions between points of
the data domain that commutative kernels miss~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}. That
construction was devised for periodic functional regression; it has not been
brought to bear on time-ordered hardware telemetry, on causal monitoring, or on
unsupervised detection. Bridging that gap is the object of this work.

This study is the eighteenth entry in a program that treats spectral truncation of
operators as a unifying primitive for resource-accounted, CPU-reproducible
quantum-AI methods, and the causal spectral-truncation kernel imports that primitive
into hardware reliability monitoring. The program spans query-efficient and
uncertainty-calibrated QAOA through graph-conditioned trust
regions~\citep{huynh2026gctr,huynh2026gctrcal,huynh2026gctrcalpro}, the measurement
cost and certified query budgets of low-depth
optimization~\citep{huynh2026meascost,huynh2026certqb}, topology-conditioned
parameter transfer and operator-spectral priors for QAOA warm
starts~\citep{huynh2026paramxfer,huynh2026paramxferB,huynh2026ostqaoa,huynh2026topoqaoa},
commutator-graph scheduling and Lie-algebraic truncation of the Trotter
residual~\citep{huynh2026topoham,huynh2026lie}, transfer-operator and graph-neural
decoding of structured and correlated quantum
noise~\citep{huynh2026gnndec,huynh2026topoqec,huynh2026covdec,huynh2026fiber}, and
structure-preserving learning of open-system dynamics and of quantum phases through
operator-system and directed spectral
truncation~\citep{huynh2026cptppinn,huynh2026dsto}. The present kernel inherits the
causal, time-respecting truncation of operators from that line and is complemented
by the fixed-depth and representation-theoretic Hamiltonian-simulation results of
Nguyen and Jing~\citep{nguyen2025zassenhaus,jing2026complexity}.

We tackle these challenges with three contributions. \textbf{(i)} We introduce the
\emph{causal spectral-truncation kernel}, a C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}%
-algebra-valued positive-definite kernel on telemetry windows whose truncation
order $n$ interpolates continuously from a commutative instantaneous monitor
($n{=}1$) to a noncommutative monitor that represents ordered, lagged
cross-channel correlations ($n{>}1$). It is the causal, time-respecting
counterpart of the periodic spectral-truncation
kernel~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}, and it subsumes the low-rank reconstruction
detector~\citep{malhotra2016lstmad} and the multivariate ridge forecaster as
commutative special cases, so the family is a strict generalization of established
monitors rather than a competitor to them. \textbf{(ii)} We prove and demonstrate
that noncommutativity is \emph{necessary}: on a physically motivated
correlated-decoherence benchmark engineered so the drift lives in ordered, lagged
cross-channel structure, the commutative monitors we evaluate --- raw-level,
instantaneous-covariance, and the periodic spectral-truncation kernel --- all
detect at chance (ROC-AUC $\approx0.5$), whereas the causal kernel detects at ROC-AUC~$0.90$ at a
certifiable optimal truncation order $n{=}2$. \textbf{(iii)} We supply the
supporting theory --- positive definiteness for every order, a blindness theorem
for commutative monitors, and an \emph{optimal-truncation detection certificate}
that is the unsupervised-detection analog of the representation--complexity bound
governing spectral-truncation kernels in regression --- and show that on smooth
marginal forecasting, where noncommutativity is provably unnecessary, the same
kernel attains $72\%$ eight-step skill over persistence. The non-monotone optimal
order is a \emph{built-in} feature of the construction, not a tuned hyperparameter,
and the entire pipeline is training-free at inference, installs with \texttt{pip},
and regenerates in seconds on a single CPU.

% ── Results ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Results}

The pipeline is summarized in Fig.~\ref{fig:overview}. A physically motivated
multi-qubit telemetry generator emits a multivariate calibration stream; sliding
windows are mapped, through the causal spectral-truncation kernel, into a
C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra whose truncation order $n$ fixes the
noncommutativity available to the monitor; and two heads --- a forecaster and an
unsupervised detector --- are each scored by the metric matched to its objective
(horizon-resolved mean absolute error, MAE, for forecasting; the threshold-free
area under the receiver-operating-characteristic curve, ROC-AUC, for detection).
The structure of the family is the structure of the result: the commutative member
($n{=}1$) governs smooth marginal forecasting and level-based drift, while the
noncommutative members ($n{>}1$) govern correlated, crosstalk-like drift. We
establish this division in four steps --- the two drift geometries, forecasting,
the kernel itself, and detection --- and then certify it analytically.

\begin{figure*}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{fig0_overview.pdf}
  \caption{\textbf{The causal spectral-truncation monitoring pipeline.} A
  physically motivated generator produces seeded multi-qubit calibration telemetry
  ($Q=5$ qubits, $C=7$ channels). Each length-$L$ sliding window $X$ is represented
  inside the channel C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra
  $\Mc=M_C(\mathbb{R})$ through the truncated causal shift,
  $K_n(X,Y)=\sum_{\tau=0}^{n-1}w_\tau\,X^{\top}S^{\tau}Y$, where $S$ is the causal
  lower shift and the truncation order $n$ sets the noncommutativity that the
  representation carries: $n{=}1$ is the commutative instantaneous covariance,
  $n{\ge}2$ adds ordered, lagged cross-channel coordinates. Two heads read this
  representation --- a ridge forecaster and an unsupervised reconstruction detector.
  The commutative member ($n{=}1$) governs forecasting and marginal drift; the
  noncommutative members ($n{>}1$) govern correlated crosstalk drift. Every figure
  and metric regenerates deterministically from fixed integer seeds on a single
  CPU.}
  \label{fig:overview}
\end{figure*}

\subsection{Two drift geometries: forecastable marginal drift and hidden
correlated decoherence}

We model a five-qubit processor sampled every half hour for one hundred hours.
Each \T\ trajectory follows a mean-reverting process superposing a slow
qubit-dependent oscillation, a linear secular decay, and Gaussian fluctuation,
with \Ttwo, gate fidelities, readout error, error-per-Clifford, and
cross-resonance phase generated by coupled processes that track \T\ (Methods). The
telemetry wanders over tens of microseconds and repeatedly dips below the
\SI{50}{\micro\second} operational threshold (Fig.~\ref{fig:dynamics}a). Crucially,
the drift is not white noise: the mean autocorrelation of detrended \T\ remains
above $0.5$ for roughly seven hours before decaying (Fig.~\ref{fig:dynamics}b), so
near-future coherence is genuinely predictable from the recent past --- the
structure the forecaster exploits below.

The second drift geometry, correlated decoherence, is qualitatively different and
is the harder target. We model it as a shared latent disturbance injected into
several channels at channel-specific propagation delays under
\emph{variance-preserving} mixing, so that every per-channel marginal variance and,
in the stationary limit, the instantaneous (lag-$0$) cross-channel covariance match
nominal operation; the disturbance lives predominantly in the \emph{ordered,
lagged} cross-channel correlation (Methods). Figure~\ref{fig:dynamics}c locates the
resulting signature precisely: averaged over channel pairs, the nominal-versus-drift
separation is an order of magnitude smaller at lag $\tau{=}0$ (mean $0.008$) than at
lag $\tau{=}1$ (mean $0.089$), so the signal is concentrated exactly where a
commutative monitor cannot look. A small finite-window residual survives at
$\tau{=}0$, but the commutative monitors we evaluate are at chance regardless
(below): this is the regime in which noncommutativity is decisive.

\begin{figure*}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{fig1_dynamics.pdf}
  \caption{\textbf{The two drift geometries.} (\textbf{a}) \T\ relaxation-time
  trajectories for all five qubits over \SI{100}{\hour}; the dashed line marks the
  \SI{50}{\micro\second} operational threshold below which a step is labeled
  drifted. (\textbf{b}) Mean autocorrelation of detrended \T\ versus lag, averaged
  across the $n=5$ qubits (shaded band, $\pm1$~s.d.\ across qubits); the slow decay
  is the forecastable structure the ridge forecaster exploits in
  Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}. (\textbf{c}) The noncommutative drift signature: the
  nominal-versus-drift gap in the causal cross-channel correlation features
  $\Phi_n(X)_{cc'\tau}$, averaged over channel pairs, as a function of lag $\tau$.
  The gap is an order of magnitude smaller at $\tau{=}0$ (mean $0.008$) than at
  $\tau{\ge}1$ (mean $0.089$), so the drift is concentrated in the lagged structure
  that a commutative ($n{=}1$) monitor cannot resolve.}
  \label{fig:dynamics}
\end{figure*}

\subsection{Coherence is forecastable, and here noncommutativity is unnecessary}

We segment the telemetry into sliding windows of length $32$ predicting an
eight-step \T\ horizon, under a leak-free $80/20$ chronological split, and compare
four forecasters --- last-value persistence, climatology, an autoregressive ridge
on the \T\ history, and a multivariate ridge on all seven channels (the commutative
$n{=}1$ member of the kernel family) --- aggregated over five telemetry-generator
seeds (Methods). Forecasting is both feasible and sharply structured
(Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}, Table~\ref{tab:forecast}). One step ahead the
multivariate ridge attains $1.80\pm0.09$~\si{\micro\second} MAE against
$2.44\pm0.16$~\si{\micro\second} for persistence; persistence then degrades steeply
with horizon (to $6.79\pm0.18$~\si{\micro\second} at eight steps) while the learned
forecasters stay nearly flat ($1.88\pm0.06$~\si{\micro\second}). The decisive
quantity is therefore the \emph{margin}: skill over persistence \emph{grows} with
the horizon, from $26\%$ one step ahead to $72\%$ eight steps ahead
(Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}b), a behavior we derive in closed form from mean
reversion in Theorem~\ref{thm:skill}.

Increasing the kernel's truncation order leaves this picture unchanged
(Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}c): the CST forecaster's eight-step skill is flat in $n$,
moving only from $72\%$ at $n{=}1$ to $71\%$ at $n{=}4$. On smooth, mean-reverting
marginal telemetry the commutative member is already near-optimal, and the
noncommutative coordinates neither help nor hurt. This is the exact complement of
the detection result that follows --- noncommutativity is decisive precisely when
the drift lives in ordered cross-channel structure, and superfluous otherwise ---
and it is what licenses the operational rule we state in the Discussion.

\begin{figure*}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{fig2_forecasting.pdf}
  \caption{\textbf{Learned forecasting beats persistence by a widening margin, and
  noncommutativity is unnecessary.} (\textbf{a}) MAE versus forecast horizon for the
  four forecasters (mean over $n=5$ telemetry-generator seeds; shaded bands
  $\pm1$~s.d.). Persistence degrades steeply with horizon while the learned ridge
  forecasters stay nearly flat. (\textbf{b}) Skill over persistence,
  $1-\mathrm{MAE}/\mathrm{MAE}_{\text{persistence}}$, for the two learned
  forecasters; the advantage \emph{grows} with horizon, as predicted by
  Theorem~\ref{thm:skill}. (\textbf{c}) Eight-step skill of the CST forecaster
  versus truncation order $n$ --- the parameter controlling the kernel's
  noncommutativity in \eqref{eq:Kn} --- aggregated over the same $n=5$ seeds (shaded
  band $\pm1$~s.d.). The curve is flat because the commutative ($n{=}1$) member already
  captures the smooth marginal structure, so the noncommutative coordinates add
  nothing here --- the precise complement of Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}.}
  \label{fig:forecast}
\end{figure*}

