\subsection{The causal spectral-truncation kernel}

We now make the central object precise. A telemetry window is
$X\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times C}$ ($L=32$ time steps, $C=7$ channels). Let $S$ be the
causal lower shift, $(Sv)_t=v_{t-1}$. The order-$n$ causal spectral-truncation
kernel represents the window inside the channel C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra
$\Mc=M_C(\mathbb{R})$ through the truncated shift powers $\{S^\tau:0\le\tau<n\}$,
\begin{equation}
  K_n(X,Y)=\sum_{\tau=0}^{n-1}w_\tau\,X^{\top}S^{\tau}Y\in\Mc,\qquad
  K_n(X,Y)_{cc'}=\sum_{\tau=0}^{n-1}w_\tau\,\langle X_{:,c},\,S^{\tau}Y_{:,c'}\rangle,
  \label{eq:Kn}
\end{equation}
with weights $w_\tau=1/(L-\tau)$ and the telemetry centered in time per channel.
Each entry of $K_n$ is a weighted sum of ordered, lagged cross-channel
correlations. Truncating the shift algebra to $n$ powers is the exact causal
counterpart of truncating the Fourier-multiplier algebra to $n$ modes in the
construction of Hashimoto et~al.~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}; the essential
difference is that $S$ is nilpotent and respects the arrow of time, so
\eqref{eq:Kn} is causal and is noncommutative for $n\ge2$. Concretely, the
self-representation $K_n(X,X)$ is symmetric at $n{=}1$ --- the commutative
instantaneous covariance $X^{\top}X$ --- but acquires antisymmetric lagged terms for
$n\ge2$, because $S^{\top}\neq S$ does not commute with channel selection. The
scalar realization $k_n(X,Y)=\langle\Phi_n(X),\Phi_n(Y)\rangle$, with feature
tensor $\Phi_n(X)_{cc'\tau}=w_\tau\langle X_{:,c},S^{\tau}X_{:,c'}\rangle$, is
positive definite for every order $n$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:pd}), so the kernel is a
legitimate similarity throughout the family. The unsupervised detector fits a
rank-$k$ nominal subspace in this feature space and scores a window by its residual
energy off that subspace --- a C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebraic generalization of
the low-rank reconstruction detector~\citep{malhotra2016lstmad}, which it recovers
exactly at $n{=}1$. The kernel is thus evaluated in closed form from a single pass
over the window, with no training, no iterative optimization, and no
hyperparameter beyond the order $n$ and rank $k$.

\subsection{Noncommutativity is necessary: commutative monitors are blind, the
causal kernel is not}

We evaluate detection on the correlated-decoherence benchmark over eight randomized
$70/30$ splits (Methods); the detector is fit on nominal windows only, so
randomization cannot leak a label it never uses. The outcome is a clean separation
(Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}, Table~\ref{tab:detection}). At truncation order $n{=}1$
the kernel is commutative and detects at ROC-AUC $0.51\pm0.04$ --- chance, the
empirical content of Theorem~\ref{thm:blind}, because the benchmark matches exactly
the marginals and the population instantaneous covariance that the commutative
member reads. At $n{=}2$ the kernel becomes noncommutative and ROC-AUC jumps to
$0.90\pm0.02$ (Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}a) --- the single largest effect in the study,
a $0.39$ swing produced by adding one lagged coordinate. Increasing $n$ further then
\emph{degrades} detection monotonically --- to $0.83$ at $n{=}3$, $0.65$ at $n{=}8$,
and back toward chance as $n\to L$ --- because each lag beyond the informative one
contributes only noise coordinates that dilute the fixed-rank nominal subspace. Both
endpoints, the commutative $n{=}1$ and the over-complete $n\to L$, sit at chance,
with a sharp interior optimum at $n{=}2$. This non-monotone profile is the
optimal-truncation certificate of Theorem~\ref{thm:optn} made visible: the
unsupervised-detection analog of the representation--complexity trade-off that
governs spectral-truncation kernels in
regression~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}. The $(n,k)$ map
(Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}b) confirms that the effect is not an artifact of a
particular rank --- the entire $n{=}1$ row is at chance and the $n{=}2$ row is bright
across every bottleneck rank.

The comparison that establishes the contribution is against other kernels
(Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}c, Table~\ref{tab:detection}). On this benchmark the
raw-level reconstruction detector scores $0.49\pm0.03$, the commutative kernel
$0.46\pm0.02$, and --- tellingly --- the \emph{periodic} spectral-truncation kernel of
Hashimoto et~al., applied unchanged to these windows, scores $0.47\pm0.03$: all
three are at chance. Only the causal spectral-truncation kernel separates the
classes, at $0.84\pm0.02$ at matched bottleneck rank and $0.90$ at its optimum. The
periodic kernel fails not because spectral truncation is the wrong idea but because
its \emph{circular} truncation smears the causal delay signature across the window
boundary, whereas the causal lower-shift truncation aligns exactly with the
propagation delays that define the drift. The decisive ingredient is therefore
causality, not truncation alone: it is what lets the kernel see an event that is
invisible to every monitor lacking an arrow of time.

\begin{figure*}[t]
