  (\textbf{a}) Detection ROC-AUC versus truncation order $n$ (mean over eight
  randomized $70/30$ splits; shaded band $\pm1$~s.d.). The commutative endpoint
  ($n{=}1$) and the raw-level monitor (dotted) sit at chance (dashed line); the
  noncommutative kernel peaks sharply at $n{=}2$ (marker, ROC-AUC $0.90$) and
  collapses back toward chance as the representation becomes over-complete --- the
  certified profile of Theorem~\ref{thm:optn}. (\textbf{b}) Detection ROC-AUC over
  the grid of truncation order $n$ and bottleneck rank $k$: the $n{=}1$ row is
  uniformly at chance and the $n{=}2$ row is uniformly high, so the effect is robust
  to the choice of rank. (\textbf{c}) Kernel comparison at matched bottleneck rank:
  the raw-level monitor, the commutative ($n{=}1$) kernel, and the periodic
  spectral-truncation kernel~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral} are all at chance, and
