\subsection{Operating characteristic and the over-complete collapse}

Figure~\ref{fig:roc}a contrasts the receiver-operating characteristics directly: on
a held-out split the causal kernel at $n{=}2$ achieves AUC $0.86$ while the
commutative kernel traces the chance diagonal (AUC $0.46$). Figure~\ref{fig:roc}b
fixes the bottleneck rank and sweeps the truncation order in isolation, exhibiting
the over-complete collapse cleanly: detection rises from chance at $n{=}1$ to its
peak at $n{=}2$ and decays back toward chance as the order grows. This is the
truncation-axis counterpart of the rank-axis over-completeness familiar from
low-rank detectors~\citep{malhotra2016lstmad}, and both axes are governed by the
\emph{same} certificate (Theorem~\ref{thm:optn}): a monitor expressive enough to
reconstruct the drift coordinates as faithfully as the nominal ones cannot separate
them. Over-expressiveness, not under-expressiveness, is the failure mode at large
$n$ --- which is why a small, fixed truncation order is the right design point.

\begin{figure*}[t]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{fig4_detection.pdf}
  \caption{\textbf{Operating characteristic and the over-complete collapse.}
  (\textbf{a}) Receiver-operating-characteristic curves on a held-out split: the
  causal spectral-truncation kernel at $n{=}2$ (solid, AUC $0.86$) versus the
  commutative kernel at $n{=}1$ (dashed, AUC $0.46$), which tracks the chance
  diagonal (dotted). (\textbf{b}) Detection ROC-AUC versus truncation order $n$ at
  fixed bottleneck rank $k=8$ (mean over eight splits; shaded band $\pm1$~s.d.),
  isolating the interior optimum at $n{=}2$ and the collapse toward chance as the
  representation becomes over-complete.}
  \label{fig:roc}
\end{figure*}

% ── Theory ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\subsection{Theory: a C\texorpdfstring{$^\ast$}{*}-algebraic kernel whose
truncation order certifies detectability}

Each empirical claim above rests on a theorem, and we state them together so the
results read as consequences rather than coincidences. The kernel is a
positive-definite, C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra-valued kernel for every order
$n$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:pd}); the commutative $n{=}1$ member is provably blind to
drift living in ordered, lagged cross-channel correlations, which the
noncommutative $n{>}1$ member resolves (Theorem~\ref{thm:blind}); the
reconstruction detector built on the kernel has a non-monotone, certifiable optimal
truncation order (Theorem~\ref{thm:optn}); ROC-AUC is the scale-free yardstick that
makes ``chance'' a precise statement throughout (Proposition~\ref{prop:auc}); and on
the forecasting side, mean reversion converts decaying autocorrelation into
horizon-growing skill (Theorem~\ref{thm:skill}). Proofs are elementary and
self-contained; we give them in full so that every quantitative claim in the paper
is traceable to a hypothesis.

\begin{theorem}[Positive definiteness of the causal C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-kernel]
\label{thm:pd}
Fix any order $n\ge1$ and nonnegative weights $w_\tau\ge0$. Then the map $K_n$ of
\eqref{eq:Kn} is a positive-definite C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra-valued
kernel: the block matrix $[K_n(X_i,X_j)]_{ij}$ is positive semidefinite over $\Mc$
for every collection of windows $X_1,\dots,X_m$, and the induced scalar kernel
$k_n$ is positive definite in the usual sense. Moreover, the self-representation
$\Phi_n(X)$ is symmetric under the channel exchange $c\leftrightarrow c'$ at $n{=}1$,
where it reduces to the commutative instantaneous covariance, and for $n\ge2$ it
carries antisymmetric lagged coordinates that no commutative member can represent.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Introduce the lifted causal feature operator
$\Psi_n(X)=\big(\sqrt{w_0}\,X,\ \sqrt{w_1}\,S^{\top}X,\ \dots,\
\sqrt{w_{n-1}}\,(S^{\top})^{\,n-1}X\big)\in\mathbb{R}^{nL\times C}$, which simply
stacks the back-shifted windows. Because $\langle X_{:,c},S^{\tau}Y_{:,c'}\rangle
=\big((S^{\top})^{\tau}X\big)_{:,c}^{\top}\big((S^{\top})^{\tau}Y\big)_{:,c'}$, the
kernel factorizes as
$K_n(X,Y)=\sum_{\tau}w_\tau\,(S^{\top\tau}X)^{\top}(S^{\top\tau}Y)
=\Psi_n(X)^{\top}\Psi_n(Y)$. Consequently, for any $c_1,\dots,c_m\in\mathbb{R}^C$,
\[
  \sum_{i,j}c_i^{\top}K_n(X_i,X_j)c_j
  =\Big\|\sum_i \Psi_n(X_i)c_i\Big\|_F^2\ \ge 0,
\]
which is precisely the defining inequality for an $\Mc$-valued positive-definite
kernel; the scalar claim follows by specializing to $C{=}1$ on the vectorized
feature $\operatorname{vec}\Phi_n$, whose Gram matrix is $k_n$. Finally, at $n{=}1$
the entry $\Phi_1(X)_{cc'}=\langle X_{:,c},X_{:,c'}\rangle$ is symmetric under
$c\leftrightarrow c'$, whereas for $\tau\ge1$ we have $S^{\tau}\neq S^{\tau\top}$, so
$\Phi_n(X)_{cc'\tau}=\langle X_{:,c},S^{\tau}X_{:,c'}\rangle\neq
\langle X_{:,c'},S^{\tau}X_{:,c}\rangle=\Phi_n(X)_{c'c\tau}$ whenever the lagged
cross-correlation is direction-dependent --- the noncommutativity.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Commutative monitors are blind to noncommutative drift]
\label{thm:blind}
Suppose nominal and drift windows are drawn from distributions $P_0,P_1$ that share
their per-channel marginals and their instantaneous cross-covariance,
$\mathbb{E}_{P_0}[\Phi_1]=\mathbb{E}_{P_1}[\Phi_1]$, yet differ in a single lagged
coordinate, $\Delta_{\tau^\star}:=\mathbb{E}_{P_1}[\Phi_{\cdot\,\cdot\,\tau^\star}]
-\mathbb{E}_{P_0}[\Phi_{\cdot\,\cdot\,\tau^\star}]\neq0$ for some $\tau^\star\ge1$.
Then every detector that depends on the data only through the order-$1$
(commutative) features $\Phi_1$ has zero first-moment separation, and hence
chance-level mean discriminability; by contrast, the order-$n$ causal kernel with
$n>\tau^\star$ separates the classes in a coordinate it actually represents, and its
mean reconstruction-score gap is bounded below by the energy of
$\Delta_{\tau^\star}$ lying outside the rank-$k$ nominal subspace.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Any monitor measurable with respect to $\Phi_1$ can separate the two classes in
mean only through $\mathbb{E}_{P_1}[\Phi_1]-\mathbb{E}_{P_0}[\Phi_1]$, which vanishes
by hypothesis; its expected score is therefore identical under $P_0$ and $P_1$, so
its mean separation is $0$ and, for the centered linear detector, its population
ROC-AUC equals $\tfrac12$ by the Mann--Whitney identity
(Proposition~\ref{prop:auc}) applied to a score with equal class means and, to first
order, equal dispersion. The order-$n$ feature map with $n>\tau^\star$, on the other
hand, contains the coordinate $\Phi_{\cdot\,\cdot\,\tau^\star}$, on which the class
means differ by $\Delta_{\tau^\star}\neq0$. Let $P_k$ denote the rank-$k$
nominal-subspace projector in feature space; the reconstruction score is
$s(X)=\norm{(I-P_k)(\Phi_n(X)-\bar\Phi)}^2$, and
$\mathbb{E}_{P_1}[s]-\mathbb{E}_{P_0}[s]\ge\norm{(I-P_k)\Delta_{\tau^\star}}^2$ up to
cross terms that vanish once $\Delta_{\tau^\star}$ is centered against the nominal
mean. Hence any nonzero component of $\Delta_{\tau^\star}$ outside the nominal
subspace produces strictly positive separation, and therefore ROC-AUC $>\tfrac12$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Optimal truncation: a detection certificate]
\label{thm:optn}
Let $e_\tau=\norm{\Delta_\tau}^2$ denote the drift energy at lag $\tau$, vanishing
beyond a maximal informative lag $\tau_{\max}$ ($e_\tau=0$ for $\tau>\tau_{\max}$),
and suppose each additional lag injects $C^2$ noise coordinates of bounded variance
into the fixed rank-$k$ nominal subspace. Then the order-$n$ detector's mean
separation-to-noise ratio is
$\rho(n)=\big(\sum_{\tau<n}e_\tau\big)^{1/2}\big/\big(\sigma^2(C^2 n-k)_+\big)^{1/2}$,
and $\rho$ is unimodal in $n$ with an interior optimum $n^\star$; since detection
ROC-AUC is a strictly increasing function of $\rho$, it is unimodal with the same
optimum, and both the commutative endpoint ($n{=}1$, $\rho=0$) and the over-complete
limit ($n\to L$, $\rho\to0$) sit at chance. The optimum $n^\star$ is the smallest
$n$ at which the marginal relative signal gain drops below the marginal relative
noise cost, $e_{n}/\!\sum_{\tau<n}e_\tau<\big(N(n{+}1)-N(n)\big)/N(n)$; in particular
$n^\star=2$ whenever the drift energy is concentrated at the first informative lag
($e_1$ dominant), and $n^\star$ increases as the energy profile spreads to higher
lags, never exceeding $\tau_{\max}+1$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Set $E(n)=\sum_{\tau<n}e_\tau$, which is non-decreasing and constant for
$n>\tau_{\max}+1$, and $N(n)=\sigma^2(C^2 n-k)_+$, which is strictly increasing once
$C^2 n>k$. Then $\rho(n)^2=E(n)/N(n)$, and $\rho(n{+}1)^2>\rho(n)^2$ holds iff
$E(n{+}1)/E(n)>N(n{+}1)/N(n)$ --- equivalently, iff the relative signal increment
$e_n/E(n)$ exceeds the relative noise increment $(N(n{+}1)-N(n))/N(n)$. The latter
is positive for every $n$, since the noise floor always grows, whereas the former is
$0$ once $n>\tau_{\max}+1$ (where $e_n=0$) and is non-increasing under a concentrated
energy profile. The inequality therefore holds on an initial range of $n$ and fails
beyond it, so $\rho$ first rises and then falls: it is unimodal, with a single
interior optimum $n^\star$ at the first $n$ where the test fails. When $e_1$
dominates, the test fails already at $n{=}2$, because the small later increments
$e_2,\dots$ cannot offset the $\sqrt{n}$ growth of the noise, giving $n^\star=2$;
broader energy profiles push $n^\star$ upward, to at most $\tau_{\max}+1$. The
endpoints follow as well: $\rho=0$ at $n{=}1$ by Theorem~\ref{thm:blind}, and
$\rho\to0$ as $n\to L$ by dilution --- the over-complete chance-level collapse.
\end{proof}

\noindent Theorem~\ref{thm:optn} is the unsupervised-detection counterpart of the
generalization bound that governs spectral-truncation kernels in
regression~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}: there the truncation order trades
representation power against Rademacher complexity, while here it trades captured
drift energy against the dimension of the nominal subspace. Because the
correlated-decoherence mode concentrates its energy at the first informative lag
(Fig.~\ref{fig:dynamics}c), the certificate predicts the empirical optimum at
$n^\star{=}2$ with no fitting (Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}a), and the classical
low-rank over-completeness collapse~\citep{malhotra2016lstmad} emerges as the rank
axis of the same statement. The optimal order is, in this sense, a built-in
diagnostic of the drift geometry rather than a tuned knob.

\begin{proposition}[Threshold-free ranking and scale invariance]
\label{prop:auc}
For any score $s$ and independent draws of a drift window $X^{+}$ and a nominal
window $X^{-}$, the ROC area satisfies the Mann--Whitney identity
$\mathrm{AUC}=\Pr[s(X^{+})>s(X^{-})]+\tfrac12\Pr[s(X^{+})=s(X^{-})]$.
It follows that $\mathrm{AUC}$ is invariant under every strictly increasing
reparametrization of $s$ --- in particular under per-feature affine rescaling of the
telemetry --- and that a constant score yields $\mathrm{AUC}=\tfrac12$ exactly.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Let $F_{+},F_{-}$ be the score CDFs under the drift and nominal classes. At a
threshold $\tau$ that flags $s>\tau$, we have $\mathrm{TPR}(\tau)=1-F_{+}(\tau)$ and
$\mathrm{FPR}(\tau)=1-F_{-}(\tau)$, so
$\mathrm{AUC}=\int_0^1\mathrm{TPR}\,\mathrm{d}(\mathrm{FPR})$. Substituting
$u=\mathrm{FPR}(\tau)$ gives
$\mathrm{AUC}=\int\Pr[s(X^{+})>\tau]\,\mathrm{d}F_{-}(\tau)=\Pr[s(X^{+})>s(X^{-})]$
for a continuous score, while atoms contribute $\tfrac12\Pr[s(X^{+})=s(X^{-})]$
through the trapezoidal interpolation of each jump --- which is exactly the
normalized Mann--Whitney $U$. Since strictly monotone maps preserve every order and
tie event, they preserve $\mathrm{AUC}$; and a constant score turns every comparison
into a tie, so $\mathrm{AUC}=0+\tfrac12\cdot1=\tfrac12$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}[Horizon-growing forecast skill]
\label{thm:skill}
Let $\{x_t\}$ be weakly stationary and zero-mean, with variance $\gamma_0>0$ and
autocorrelation $\rho(h)=\operatorname{Corr}(x_{t+h},x_t)$. Persistence,
$\hat{x}_{t+h}=x_t$, incurs the mean-squared $h$-step risk
$R_{\mathrm{pers}}(h)=2\gamma_0(1-\rho(h))$, whereas the optimal single-lag linear
forecast $\hat{x}_{t+h}=\rho(h)x_t$ incurs
$R_\star(h)=\gamma_0(1-\rho(h)^2)\le R_{\mathrm{pers}}(h)$; the relative skill is thus
$S(h)=1-R_\star/R_{\mathrm{pers}}=(1-\rho(h))/2$. Wherever $\rho$ is non-increasing,
$S(h)$ is non-decreasing and bounded above by $\tfrac12$. For a first-order
autoregressive process, $\rho(h)=\phi^{\,h}$, so the single measured number
$\phi=\rho(1)$ fixes the entire skill curve.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Take the one-parameter predictor $\hat{x}_{t+h}=ax_t$. Then
$\mathbb{E}[(x_{t+h}-ax_t)^2]=\gamma_0(1-2a\rho(h)+a^2)$ is a strictly convex
parabola in $a$, minimized at $a^\star=\rho(h)$ and giving
$R_\star=\gamma_0(1-\rho(h)^2)$, while $a{=}1$ recovers
$R_{\mathrm{pers}}=2\gamma_0(1-\rho(h))$. Dividing the two yields
$R_\star/R_{\mathrm{pers}}=(1+\rho(h))/2$, so $S(h)=(1-\rho(h))/2$, which is strictly
decreasing in $\rho$; hence wherever $\rho(h)$ decreases in $h$ the skill $S(h)$
increases, and $S\le\tfrac12$ on $\rho\in[0,1]$. For an AR(1) process, iterating the
recursion gives $\operatorname{Cov}(x_{t+h},x_t)=\phi^{\,h}\gamma_0$, whence
$\rho(h)=\phi^{\,h}$ and $S(h)=(1-\phi^{\,h})/2$, which increases from $0$ toward
$\tfrac12$.
\end{proof}

\noindent Theorem~\ref{thm:skill} is a lower bound that uses only the single most
recent sample; the multivariate ridge (the commutative $n{=}1$ member) exceeds it by
exploiting the full $32$-step, seven-channel history, which is why its measured
eight-step skill reaches $72\%$ (Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}). The noncommutative
coordinates add nothing in this regime because the marginal forecasting structure is
already linear and instantaneous --- the exact complement of the detection regime, in
which those same coordinates are everything. Together the two theorems delimit when
noncommutativity is necessary and when it is superfluous, which is the operational
content of the work.

% ── Discussion ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Discussion}

We have recast quantum-hardware reliability monitoring as operator-algebraic
learning and distilled the result into a single operational rule: \emph{match the
kernel's noncommutativity to the geometry of the drift}. Level-based and
instantaneous monitors --- including the periodic spectral-truncation kernel from
which our construction descends --- are blind to correlated decoherence that lives in
ordered, lagged cross-channel structure, which is the very failure mode that quantum
error correction is least able to absorb. The causal spectral-truncation kernel
resolves it, and an elementary certificate (Theorem~\ref{thm:optn}) both explains
why a small truncation order is optimal and predicts, with no fitting, where that
optimum sits. Because the kernel recovers established forecasting and low-rank
detection at its commutative order, the family is a strict generalization of
existing monitors rather than a competitor, and inherits their interpretability
while extending their reach. Deep sequence-model monitors --- recurrent
\citep{hochreiter1997lstm,cho2014gru} and attention-based
\citep{vaswani2017attention} architectures studied elsewhere for
telemetry~\citep{lim2021forecasting,wen2023transformers} --- are complementary but
require training and many parameters, whereas the present kernel is training-free at
inference, deterministic, and CPU-reproducible in seconds; the contribution is thus
both a theoretical characterization of when noncommutative monitoring is necessary
and a practical toolbox that runs on commodity hardware.

Several limitations bound these claims and define the natural next steps. The
telemetry generator, although physically motivated, is a model rather than measured
device data, and the correlated-decoherence mode is a controlled construction chosen
to isolate the noncommutative effect in the cleanest possible setting; validation on
archival calibration logs from operating processors and on a standard
anomaly-detection benchmark~\citep{lavin2015nab} is the priority follow-up. The
kernel as presented is linear in its feature map, so composing it with an outer
nonlinearity, and pairing the forecaster with an explicit recalibration policy under
a cost model and uncertainty-aware predictions~\citep{gal2016dropout}, are concrete
extensions toward a deployed monitor. Because the entire pipeline is open,
hardware-agnostic, and fast to reproduce, it is positioned to serve as a common,
auditable substrate for that work.

% ── Conclusions ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Conclusions}

We have introduced the causal spectral-truncation kernel and shown, both empirically
and through an elementary certificate, that the geometry of hardware drift dictates
how much noncommutativity a reliability monitor must carry. A single truncation order
interpolates from a commutative instantaneous monitor to a noncommutative one that
reads ordered, lagged cross-channel structure: on smooth marginal drift the
commutative member forecasts coherence with horizon-growing skill, whereas on
correlated decoherence --- the failure mode quantum error correction can least absorb
--- only the noncommutative member detects the event, at a truncation order the
theory predicts with no fitting. The practical content is a single rule: match the
kernel's noncommutativity to the geometry of the drift.

Because the monitor is training-free, deterministic, and reproducible on one CPU in
seconds, it can run as a passive layer over the calibration telemetry a processor
already records, complementing rather than replacing the protocol-based
characterization that diagnoses errors on
demand~\citep{magesan2011rb,proctor2020drift,sarovar2020crosstalk}. As devices scale
toward the qubit counts at which fault tolerance becomes feasible, reliability
monitoring at that scale is itself a near-term bottleneck, and an operator-algebraic
monitor whose cost grows only linearly in the noncommutativity it exploits --- and
whose optimal complexity is certified rather than tuned --- is a concrete step toward
meeting it. We expect the same representation--complexity trade-off to organize the
monitoring of other correlated-error channels, and the kernel to compose naturally
with the nonlinear and uncertainty-aware extensions outlined above.

% ── Methods ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section{Methods}

\paragraph{Telemetry generation.}
We generate a synthetic multi-qubit dataset for $Q=5$ qubits over $N=200$ half-hour
steps. For qubit $q$ at time $t$ (in hours) the relaxation time is
$T_1(q,t)=\max(10,\,80+20\sin(2\pi t/48+0.8q)-0.05\,t+\varepsilon)$ with
$\varepsilon\sim\mathcal{N}(0,2^2)$, superposing a slow qubit-dependent oscillation,
a secular decay, and Gaussian fluctuation. The dephasing time is
$T_2=0.9\,T_1\,\eta$ with $\eta\sim\mathcal{N}(1,0.04^2)$, and the single- and
two-qubit gate fidelities, readout-assignment error, error-per-Clifford, and
cross-resonance phase are generated by analogous bounded processes carrying small
secular trends, so that all seven channels track \T\ by construction. A binary drift
label marks any step with $T_1<\SI{50}{\micro\second}$ or single-qubit fidelity
below $0.998$. Generation is fully seeded and therefore bit-for-bit reproducible.

\paragraph{Correlated-decoherence benchmark.}
The detection benchmark contrasts nominal windows with
\emph{correlated-decoherence} windows that share the same physical base trajectory
$B$ and the same per-channel noise scales $\sigma$. The drift class injects a single
shared \emph{white} latent $u$ into four channels (\T, \Ttwo, readout error,
cross-resonance phase) at channel-specific integer delays $(0,1,2,3)$ under
variance-preserving mixing
$x_c\leftarrow B_c+\sigma_c(\sqrt{1-a^2}\,\varepsilon_c+a\,u_{t-\delta_c})$ with
$a=1$. Because the latent is white, every per-channel marginal variance and every
temporal autocorrelation are left unchanged, and the population lag-$0$
cross-covariance ($\tau=0$, $\delta_c\neq\delta_{c'}$) is zero in both classes; the
entire perturbation is carried by the ordered lag-$\tau$ cross-channel covariance
($\tau=\delta_{c'}-\delta_c\ge1$). Per-window temporal centering over $L=32$ leaves a
small finite-window residual at $\tau=0$, but the drift energy is concentrated at
$\tau\ge1$ (Fig.~\ref{fig:dynamics}c). The benchmark is therefore the cleanest
possible separator: the commutative monitors we evaluate --- raw-level,
instantaneous-covariance, and the periodic spectral-truncation kernel --- are all at
chance and the drift is exposed only by the causal noncommutative ($n\ge2$) kernel,
which is the empirical content of Theorem~\ref{thm:blind}.

\paragraph{Causal spectral-truncation kernel.}
A window $X\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times C}$ ($L=32$, $C=7$) is centered in time per channel
and mapped to the feature tensor
$\Phi_n(X)_{cc'\tau}=\langle X_{:,c},S^{\tau}X_{:,c'}\rangle/(L-\tau)$ for
$\tau=0,\dots,n-1$, with $S$ the causal lower shift; the operator-valued kernel is
\eqref{eq:Kn} and the scalar kernel is the Hilbert--Schmidt inner product of these
features. The commutative member ($n{=}1$) retains only the instantaneous
covariance, and each $n{>}1$ adds one band of ordered lagged cross-channel
coordinates. For comparison we implement the \emph{periodic} spectral-truncation
baseline unchanged: it maps each channel to the $n\times n$ Toeplitz matrix of its
truncated Fourier coefficients and forms the ordered cross-channel products of those
matrices, exactly the construction of Hashimoto
et~al.~\citep{hashimoto2024spectral}. The two kernels differ only in whether the
truncated algebra is the causal shift (ours) or the periodic Fourier multiplier
(theirs), which isolates causality as the operative ingredient.

\paragraph{Forecasting.}
We compare persistence (carry the last \T\ forward), climatology (the training-mean
horizon trajectory), an autoregressive ridge on the $32$-step \T\ history, and a
multivariate ridge on the flattened $32\times7$ window (ridge penalty $\alpha=5$;
this is the commutative $n{=}1$ kernel member), under a leak-free per-qubit $80/20$
chronological split, scoring MAE per horizon step over five generator seeds with
skill $1-\mathrm{MAE}/\mathrm{MAE}_{\text{persistence}}$. The CST forecaster augments
the window with the order-$n$ causal features before the ridge solve; its eight-step
skill versus $n$ (Fig.~\ref{fig:forecast}c) is averaged over the same five seeds. The
chronological split guarantees that no future sample informs a past prediction.

\paragraph{Detection.}
The unsupervised detector standardizes the kernel feature map on nominal training
windows, fits a rank-$k$ principal subspace, and scores each test window by its mean
squared reconstruction residual outside that subspace. Detection quality is ROC-AUC
against the drift labels over eight randomized $70/30$ splits; because the detector
is fit on nominal windows only, randomization cannot leak a label it never uses. The
truncation sweep reports, per order $n$, the best ROC-AUC over bottleneck ranks
$k\in\{1,2,3,5,8,12,16\}$, and the kernel comparison (Table~\ref{tab:detection})
fixes $k=8$ so that all detectors are compared at matched representational budget.

\paragraph{Computational complexity and resource accounting.}
Each window $X\in\mathbb{R}^{L\times C}$ is mapped to a feature tensor $\Phi_n(X)$ of
$nC^2$ coordinates, every coordinate an inner product of length at most $L$, so
feature extraction costs $O(nC^2 L)$ time and $O(nC^2)$ memory per window --- linear
in the window length and the truncation order, and quadratic only in the channel
count $C$ (here $C{=}7$, $L{=}32$, and $n\le16$, for at most $784$ feature
coordinates). Fitting the detector standardizes these features and extracts a
rank-$k$ principal subspace of the $N_{\mathrm{train}}\times nC^2$ nominal feature
matrix, an
$O\!\big(N_{\mathrm{train}}\,nC^2\min(N_{\mathrm{train}},nC^2)\big)$ singular-value
decomposition; scoring a test window then costs $O(nC^2 L)$ to featurize and
$O(nC^2 k)$ to project onto the subspace and measure the residual. Every step is a
dense linear-algebra primitive with no iterative optimization, no gradients, and no
learned parameters, so the entire truncation-and-rank sweep is polynomial and runs in
seconds on a single CPU core. This is the resource counterpart of the
operating-characteristic result: the monitor is training-free at inference, and its
cost grows only linearly in the noncommutativity order $n$ that it is permitted to
exploit.

\paragraph{Reproducibility and compute.}
The analyses run entirely on a single CPU and regenerate in seconds, with no GPU and
no training. Every figure and table is computed live from the installed
\texttt{qdriftforecast} package by \texttt{make\_paper\_figures.py} (the installed
\texttt{qdrift-reproduce} entry point), and reported uncertainties are
mean~$\pm$~standard deviation across the $n=5$ generator seeds (forecasting) or $n=8$
randomized splits (detection). Determinism is byte-level: the seeds and the build
epoch are pinned and the vector PDF output is fixed across runs, so every number in
the manuscript is a reproducible function of integer seeds.

% ── Availability ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
\section*{Data availability}
The synthetic multi-qubit telemetry and the correlated-decoherence benchmark used in
this study are generated deterministically by the released code from fixed integer
seeds and require no external download. The exact metric values underlying every
figure and table are reported in the manuscript and are reproducible from the
released code.

\section*{Code availability}
The telemetry generator, the causal spectral-truncation kernel, the detection and
forecasting modules, and the figure-and-table pipeline are openly available in the
project repository under an MIT license as the installable \texttt{qdriftforecast}
package. All figures, tables, and reported uncertainties regenerate from the released
code on commodity CPU hardware in seconds.

