% ── Supplementary derivations (Appendix) ─────────────────────────────────────
\section{Supplementary derivations and reproduction details}

\noindent This appendix is a self-contained derivation of every concept the released
code implements, written for a reader with linear algebra and basic probability but
no prior exposure to quantum-hardware telemetry, operator-algebraic kernels, or the
estimators used here. Every symbol that appears in the code is defined, and each
subsection names the source file (under \texttt{submission/code/}) that realizes it,
so the appendix doubles as a guide to the artifact. The whole pipeline is CPU-only
and deterministic: every number in the paper is a fixed function of integer seeds.

\paragraph{Source-file map.} All paths are relative to \texttt{submission/code/}:
\texttt{qdriftforecast/data.py} (telemetry generator, correlated-drift benchmark,
windowing, splitting); \texttt{qdriftforecast/kernels.py} (the causal
spectral-truncation kernel, its operator- and scalar-valued forms, and the
periodic baseline); \texttt{qdriftforecast/detection.py} (the reconstruction
detector, truncation sweep, $(n,k)$ grid and kernel comparison);
\texttt{qdriftforecast/forecasting.py} (forecasters); \texttt{make\_\allowbreak
paper\_\allowbreak figures.py} (all figures and table bodies); and
\texttt{generated\_\allowbreak data/*.json} (the numbers behind each panel).

\subsection*{S1. The problem in one paragraph}
A quantum processor is not static: its coherence times, gate fidelities, readout
error, and coupling parameters drift over hours, eroding the error budget that
quantum error correction depends on, so an operator must decide \emph{when} a device
has drifted and \emph{which} intervals warrant recalibration. We pose two tasks on
the multivariate telemetry --- \emph{forecast} near-future coherence, and
\emph{detect} drifted windows without labels --- and the central finding concerns the
second: one geometry of drift, correlated decoherence living in ordered, lagged
cross-channel structure, leaves every commutative monitor we evaluate at chance and
is detectable only by a noncommutative one.

\subsection*{S2. Computation model: telemetry as arrays}
\emph{(\texttt{qdriftforecast/data.py}.)} A telemetry record is a finite table in
which each row is a \texttt{(timestamp, qubit\_id)} pair holding measured or
simulated features. The seven channels (\texttt{FEATURE\_COLS}) are \texttt{T1\_us},
\texttt{T2\_us}, \texttt{gate\_fidelity\_1q}, \texttt{gate\_fidelity\_2q},
\texttt{readout\_error}, \texttt{gate\_error\_per\_clifford}, and
\texttt{cross\_resonance\_phase\_rad}. Every result in the paper is a deterministic
function of these arrays and fixed integer seeds.

\subsection*{S3. The physics of the generator}
\emph{(\texttt{generate\_synthetic\_dataset}.)} For qubit $q$ at time $t$ the
relaxation time is
$T_1(q,t)=\max(10,\,80+20\sin(2\pi t/48+0.8q)-0.05\,t+\varepsilon)$ with
$\varepsilon\sim\mathcal{N}(0,2^2)$, superposing a $48$-hour oscillation
(recalibration-like cycling, with phase $0.8q$ decorrelating the qubits), a secular
decay (aging), and Gaussian fluctuation. The remaining channels track $T_1$ by
construction, and a binary drift label marks any step with
$T_1<\SI{50}{\micro\second}$ or single-qubit fidelity below $0.998$. Because the
deterministic part is smooth and the noise small, the detrended series is weakly
stationary with a slowly decaying autocorrelation --- the structure that S8 converts
into forecast skill.

\subsection*{S4. The correlated-decoherence benchmark, and why commutative
monitors are at chance}
\emph{(\texttt{generate\_correlated\_drift\_windows}.)} Both classes share the same
base trajectory $B$ and noise scales $\sigma$. The drift class adds a shared white
latent $u$ to four channels at delays $\delta_c\in\{0,1,2,3\}$ under
variance-preserving mixing
$x_c=B_c+\sigma_c(\sqrt{1-a^2}\,\varepsilon_c+a\,u_{t-\delta_c})$. Because $u$ is
white, three matchings hold exactly: (i) each channel's marginal variance is
$\sigma_c^2$ in both classes; (ii) each channel's temporal autocorrelation is
unchanged, since a sum of independent white processes is white; and (iii) the
\emph{population} lag-$0$ cross-covariance between two injected channels is
$a^2\sigma_c\sigma_{c'}\mathbb{E}[u_{t-\delta_c}u_{t-\delta_{c'}}]=0$ for
$\delta_c\neq\delta_{c'}$, matching nominal. The signal energy resides entirely in
the lag-$\tau$ cross-covariance with $\tau=\delta_{c'}-\delta_c\ge1$. Two caveats
bound the scope of this matching: per-window temporal centering over the finite $L=32$ window
leaves a small $O(1/L)$ residual in the centered lag-$0$ cross-covariance of the
drift class, so the matching is exact only in the stationary limit; and
Theorem~\ref{thm:blind} is a statement about \emph{first-moment} discriminability,
not about every conceivable nonlinear statistic. The operative claim is the one we
verify empirically: the commutative monitors we evaluate --- the raw-level detector,
the commutative ($n{=}1$) kernel, and the periodic spectral-truncation kernel --- are
all at chance ($n{=}1$ ROC-AUC $0.51$), because the drift energy is concentrated in
the ordered, lagged cross-channel correlations they cannot represent
(Fig.~\ref{fig:dynamics}c).

\subsection*{S5. The causal spectral-truncation kernel, from scratch}
\emph{(\texttt{qdriftforecast/kernels.py}.)} Center each channel of a window in time.
For lags $\tau=0,\dots,n-1$ form the ordered cross-channel correlation
$\Phi_n(X)_{cc'\tau}=\frac{1}{L-\tau}\sum_{t\ge\tau}X_{t,c}X_{t-\tau,c'}$, which are
the matrix elements of $X^{\top}S^{\tau}X$ with $S$ the causal lower shift. The
operator-valued kernel $K_n(X,Y)=\sum_{\tau<n}w_\tau X^{\top}S^{\tau}Y\in M_C$ is an
element of the channel C\textsuperscript{$\ast$}-algebra, and the scalar kernel is
$\langle\Phi_n(X),\Phi_n(Y)\rangle$. At $n{=}1$ this is the symmetric instantaneous
covariance and is commutative; for $n\ge2$ the lagged terms are asymmetric in
$(c,c')$ because $S^{\top}\neq S$, which is exactly the noncommutativity the result
turns on. Truncating the shift algebra to $n$ powers is the causal analog of
truncating the Fourier-multiplier algebra to $n$ modes in the spectral-truncation
construction of Hashimoto et~al., and the periodic baseline
(\texttt{periodic\_truncation\_feature\_map}) implements that original torus
construction unchanged, so the comparison in Fig.~\ref{fig:detection}c varies only
causality.

\subsection*{S6. The detector and the optimal-truncation certificate}
\emph{(\texttt{qdriftforecast/detection.py}.)} Standardize the kernel features on
nominal windows, fit a rank-$k$ principal subspace, and score a test window by its
residual energy outside it. Increasing the truncation order $n$ simultaneously
captures more drift signal (good) and admits $C^2$ noise coordinates per lag (bad),
so the separation-to-noise ratio is unimodal in $n$, peaking just past the
informative lag (Theorem~\ref{thm:optn}). Empirically the peak is at $n{=}2$ with
ROC-AUC $0.90$; the commutative endpoint and the over-complete limit are both at
chance, and the rank axis of the same certificate recovers the classical low-rank
over-completeness collapse.

\subsection*{S7. Metrics: MAE for forecasting, ROC-AUC for detection}
Forecasting uses mean absolute error per horizon step, reported step by step so the
widening gap over persistence is visible, with skill
$1-\mathrm{MAE}/\mathrm{MAE}_{\text{pers}}$. Detection uses ROC-AUC, which by the
Mann--Whitney identity (Proposition~\ref{prop:auc}) equals the probability that a
random drift window outranks a random nominal one, is invariant under per-feature
rescaling, and equals $\tfrac12$ for a constant score --- the precise chance level
that the commutative and over-complete monitors attain.

\subsection*{S8. Why forecast skill grows with the horizon}
This is Theorem~\ref{thm:skill}. For a weakly stationary process with
autocorrelation $\rho(h)$, the persistence risk is $2\gamma_0(1-\rho(h))$ and the
best single-lag predictor's risk is $\gamma_0(1-\rho(h)^2)$, so the skill is
$(1-\rho(h))/2$, which increases as $\rho$ decays. The multivariate ridge uses the
full history and exceeds this single-lag bound, reaching $72\%$ at horizon eight,
while the noncommutative coordinates add nothing because the marginal structure is
already linear and instantaneous (S5).

\subsection*{S9. How to reproduce everything}
\par\sloppy
Install with \texttt{pip install qdriftforecast} (or, from a checkout,
\texttt{pip install submission/code}). Run \texttt{qdrift-reproduce} (equivalently
\texttt{python -m qdriftforecast.reproduce} or \texttt{python
make\_\allowbreak paper\_\allowbreak figures.py} from \texttt{submission/code/}).
The script writes, deterministically from fixed seeds on a single CPU: the five
vector PDF figures into \texttt{../figures/}; the three table bodies into
\texttt{../tables/} (\texttt{forecasting\_\allowbreak benchmark.tex},
\texttt{detection\_\allowbreak benchmark.tex},
\texttt{truncation\_\allowbreak sweep.tex}); and the machine-readable source data
into \texttt{generated\_\allowbreak data/*.json}. No number in the manuscript is
typed by hand; each is emitted by this pipeline.

\subsection*{S10. What the result means, and what it does not}
A small, training-free, noncommutative kernel detects a correlated-decoherence drift
that every commutative monitor --- including the periodic spectral-truncation kernel
--- misses entirely, and a single truncation order certifies how much
noncommutativity to use. Coherence forecasting succeeds wherever autocorrelation
persists, and there noncommutativity is unnecessary. We make no quantum-hardware
superiority claim: the telemetry is a physically motivated model and the
correlated-decoherence mode is a controlled construction chosen to isolate the
noncommutative effect. What the work delivers is a reusable, leakage-controlled,
CPU-reproducible, operator-algebraic foundation for quantum-processor reliability
monitoring, together with a demonstration --- both empirical and certified --- that the
geometry of the drift dictates the noncommutativity a monitor must have.

